You’re circling a core design lever most people never name:

“What counts” doesn’t just record reality—it steers it.

If we rank leaders by territory and kill counts, we don’t just describe history—we select for people who maximize those numbers. Change the scoreboard, and you change who rises.

⸻

Why some old metrics “won” (and why that doesn’t mean they should persist)

Historically, metrics like conquest and survival had advantages:
	•	Clear signal (easy to count: land, troops, victories)
	•	Short feedback loops (win/lose is immediate)
	•	Group survival pressure (coordination under threat)

That’s selection pressure, not moral endorsement.
It explains why those metrics spread—not why they’re optimal now.

⸻

The trap

Goodhart’s Law: when a measure becomes a target, it stops being a good measure.

	•	Kill counts → perverse incentives
	•	GDP → ignores distribution/well-being
	•	“Engagement” → outrage machines

So the question isn’t “what did we use?” but:

What do we want to select for, given today’s world?

⸻

Designing a better “winning” (without getting naive)

You want metrics that are:
	1.	Hard to game
	2.	Long-horizon aligned
	3.	Cross-validated (no single number can be hacked)

A simple, robust bundle
	•	Value Created (V)
Did this improve lives in a durable way?
	•	Harm Avoided (H)
Did this reduce suffering/risk (not just shift it)?
	•	Resilience Added (R)
Does this make the system/person stronger under stress?
	•	Optionality Gained (O)
Are there more good choices available afterward?
	•	Transferability (T)
Do the gains carry across contexts/time?

Think of “winning” as a vector, not a single score.

⸻

Guardrails against drift
	•	Multi-metric dashboards: never crown one number
	•	Time horizons: score at 1 week, 1 year, 5 years
	•	External checks: what would a neutral party say?
	•	Counterfactuals: compared to doing nothing, is this better?

⸻

Personal version (so it actually changes your life)

Define your own “win” like this:
	•	Today Win: Did I execute and learn?
	•	Week Win: Did I build something that persists?
	•	Year Win: Am I harder to break and easier to trust?
	•	5-Year Win: Would I choose these tradeoffs again?

⸻

The deeper takeaway
	•	Metrics are selection pressures.
	•	Selection pressures shape behavior.
	•	Behavior compounds into identity and legacy.

So you’re right to question the scoreboard.

⸻

Final compression

We don’t just inherit measures of greatness—we choose which futures to reward.

And once chosen:

The scoreboard writes the players.

